project     = TestProject
sha         = e9ff00a37014a4721f35f6fbb1bd1fb5f608d5b4
author      = Kevin Sawicki
commit date = 2012-12-03
log         = Load embedded images using contents API	Previously repository paths embedded as images in	comments, issues, etc. were requested by including	username/password credentials in a standard HTTP	request.	This is no longer possible now that OAuth tokens	are used in the app and these URLs do not accept	authenticate using tokens.  The contents API does	support OAuth tokens and can be used to request	embedded images that start with blob or raw in	their paths.

author      = Kevin Sawicki
commit date = 2012-09-06
log         = Delegate menu creation from activity to current fragment	Menu items would previously occasionally not be selectable	on Gingerbread and possibly other platforms when fragments	in a ViewPager were contributing menu items.  Now the	activity delegates directly to the fragments to create	the options menu and the fragments no longer call	setHasOptionsMenu which appears to remove the problem and	the menu items are now always selectable.	Closes issue #178

------ Sha Details -----
project     = TestProject
sha         = 389efa64586c6ff2a9a5e6c0b8bcfb171dad4d88
author      = Kevin Sawicki
commit date = 2012-04-25
log         = Put list item update logic in list adapter extensions	Storing details on updating the view inside the holders	presents complexity since holders have to do the bookkeeping	and that often requires extra objects being stored and logic	being run once per view holder.	Moving this to the adapter allows it to be computed once	and reset when the items change and doesn't require storing	state between all the holders.	The new pattern is to create an ItemView extension that exposes	public final fields for each view element that get updated and	then the list adapter will contain the logic on how the view	should be updated.	
is_bug      = False

	------ Patch -----
	language    = java
	file        = app/src/main/java/com/github/mobile/android/issue/IssueDashboardPagerAdapter.java
	is_test     = False

sha         = 4d046767183b3931c4f9c005ac4bbe361f9b424a
author      = Kevin Sawicki
commit date = 2012-04-23
log         = Switch back to showing markdown in text views	Reusing web views for changing web content proved an overall	poor user experience, was slow, jittery, and sometimes unreliable	about reported sizes.	Switch back to using a text view with custom spans to display	HTML markdown for issues and comments. The HTML returned from	API v3 is slight massaged to remove certain elements and slightly	alter padding and whitespace.	This brings back the Html and HttpImageGetter classes but	adds further support for supporting tags not currently	handled by the built-in Android Html class.

sha         = 7ac319bf2acacc444aebc79c0d233d78bfa9eecd
author      = Roberto Tyley
commit date = 2012-04-22
log         = add integration test for Org switcher and Org repo-list display	This just pages through the Orgs and checks that the repo list updates	to show at least one repo name known to be in the selected org. I've	added this test because I recently unwittingly broke the Org switcher	with 6708c75- the associated code is fragile and I'd like to make sure I	don't break it again! I'm a little concerned that the integration test	itself might be rather brittle but time will tell on that front...	This commit includes a tweak to cope with pre-ICS Spinner by ABS:	Instead of android.widget.Spinner, ABS uses	'com.actionbarsherlock.internal.widget.IcsSpinner' for the actionbar	dropdown on pre-ICS devices, so the integration test was failing to find	the dropdown on pre-ics devices.

sha         = c07c1f71fc4193fad8db8b918075332b752965b7
author      = Roberto Tyley
commit date = 2012-04-16
log         = Fix recently-viewed repos - 'Recent' labels now show correctly	This changes the implementation of RecentReposHelper to base it off a	single recently-used list, rather than one list per User/Org context.	I think this'll make it easier to add repos to the recently used-list	when spontaneously viewing repos without an explicit User/Org context,	and would make generating an overall list of most-recently viewed repos	easier if one was required.	The list of recently viewed repos help is now longer, at a maximum of 20	items, but only 5 'recently viewed' repos are displayed in each Org	context - the extra is to ensure that viewing 5 or more repos in one Org	context doesn't completely deplete the recent-repos in another.	
is_bug      = False

------ Sha Details -----
project     = TestProject
sha         = cef859c86bd0ba7d01fdc7a6b33d69a7d2d12928
author      = Roberto Tyley
commit date = 2012-04-05
log         = Fix initiation/ensuring of user-login	The problem with making sure the user is authenticated is that getting	them to sign in is a process that will block, so you can't reasonably	expect anything that occurs on the main thread to have a guaranteed	reference to authenticated GitHub credentials.	Fortunately, when people are doing network access it *has* to be on a	background thread. We can enforce that these background threads have	required the user to login, so at the point of executing the api	request, we will have credentials and can set them on the request.	Implementation-wise the important classes for this change are	AuthenticatedUserLoader & AuthenticatedUserTask, which enforce	that the user must be signed in before the rest of their background	threads run, LateAuthenticatedGitHubClient which only attempts to read	the GitHub credentials immediately before making it's API request	(which is implicitly on the background thread) and GitHubAccountScope,	a custom Guice scope used by the a
is_bug      = False

	------ Patch -----
	language    = java
	file        = app/src/main/java/com/github/mobile/android/DashboardActivity.java
	is_test     = False
		method      = onResume
		total_add   = 0
		total_del   = 5
		excepDict   = {}

------ Sha Details -----
project     = TestProject
sha         = 2b8afd50f9547f3c626ce6198a0727936e10ffc2
author      = Roberto Tyley
commit date = 2012-03-30
log         = Remove Avatar sqlite storage as it's now on disk, post 3fb3081	The default implementation of lazy-drawables storage is to cache to the	filesystem, which I think is appropriate for avatar blobs, as they are	not going to have db queries constructed on them.	Because our avatar file store is in the app's 'cache' folder we also get	a couple of nice things for free: the folder will be automatically	cleared by the operating system if disk space is tight, which is better than	us swelling a database file which can't be easily shrunk by the OS. The	android platform also gives the user the option to clear an apps cache	on the 'manage app' page - the user can use this as a brute-force	method to refresh their avatars.	
is_bug      = False

	------ Patch -----
	language    = java
	file        = app/src/main/java/com/github/mobile/android/persistence/AccountDataManager.java
	is_test     = False

project     = TestProject
sha         = 3fb30810f1cfcdeac71dfb9a796ae869130d578f
author      = Roberto Tyley
commit date = 2012-03-30
log         = Fix #18 : avatars duplicated on initial load	This fix switches the implementation of AvatarHelper (which used the	'tag' field of the ImageView for tracking loaded updates) to use	https://github.com/rtyley/lazy-drawables (which uses a custom drawable	that updates itself to the same end).	some other small improvements:	* keys off gravatar id rather than the avatar_url supplied by the GitHub	api. This allows us to show avatars against commits, even though those	commits may have been made by people who aren't GitHub users, and allows	us to use the same pool of avatar images for both	* avatar images in the in-memory cache are pre-scaled to the right size	for the ImageView, which saves the android platform from having to do it	whenever the avatar is re-used - helps performance on scrolling thru big	lists	* uses streaming on download to avoid allocating a full byte array for	the compressed image data	* does a bit more work (decompressing image data) on the non-UI thread,	to avoid jerkiness	al
is_bug      = True

------ Sha Details -----
project     = TestProject
sha         = 7ca53e8f9438b63b2a4cde2e358a21d9389c20fc
author      = Roberto Tyley
commit date = 2012-03-21
log         = Add Android Beam for Issues	The Beam API calls are wrapped in the 'Beam' class, so that the	classloaders of earlier devices don't throw exceptions.	To get Beam to work, you need to specify in your activity code that	you're going to broadcast a Beam message, and in your manifest that	your activity is interested in receiving particular Beam messages. We	filter here by specifying the "application/vnd.github.repo.issue+json"	mime type for messages.	The integration test exposed an interesting bug in robotium - if you	decide to skip the body of a test (eg because beam isn't available for	the device under test), the teardown method will hang on the robotium	method finishOpenedActivities() - it has a lethal little loop that	doesn't die:	https://github.com/jayway/robotium/blob/robotium-3.1/robotium-solo/src/main/java/com/jayway/android/robotium/solo/ActivityUtils.java#L120..L122	NFC & Beam documentation:	http://developer.android.com/guide/topics/nfc/nfc.html	
is_bug      = True

	------ Patch -----

sha         = 242757ac92dc5a0ebf7d1e81c7daf360913d3af6
author      = Roberto Tyley
commit date = 2012-03-21
log         = Make sure proguard knows about the concise newArraylist() from Guava	I wanted to use the concise no-generic-declaration newArraylist() method	from Guava in the integration tests, but because the Guava library is	used in the main app, and proguard didn't see the newArraylist() method	there, it stripped it out and the integration test failed with a	'unable to resolve static method' dalvik VM error.	Rather than futz about with a proguard rule, this commit just ensures	that the method is seen in the main app, so proguard doesn't strip it	out.
